article.description: Heather Bowman scored 16 points, Janelle Bekkering added 11 of her 14 in the second half, and Gonzaga beat San Diego 66-55 Monday in the WCC tournament final.
article.headline: Gonzaga headed to NCAA tourney for just 2nd time in school history
article.linkText: Gonzaga wins WCC final, earns rare NCAA trip
article.story:
LAS VEGAS -- One year to the day after San Diego ruined Gonzaga's NCAA tournament plans, Janelle Bekkering and her fellow Zags finally gave a performance befitting the West Coast Conference's best team for the past half-decade.

Heather Bowman scored 16 points, Bekkering added 11 of her 14 in the second half, and Gonzaga beat San Diego 66-55 Monday in the schools' second straight meeting in the WCC tournament final.

Kelly Bowen had 15 points and nine rebounds for the Zags (26-6), who cut down the nets and danced with their legion of fans from Spokane after earning a trip to the NCAAs for just the second time in school history. Courtney Vandersloot added 10 points and 10 assists to the 15th win in 17 games for the Zags, who have won five straight West Coast regular-season titles.

This victory also nipped a growing stigma for Gonzaga, which has lost three conference tournament games in the past four years. San Diego kept the Zags out of the NCAA tournament last year, winning the title game on the Toreros' home court -- a coincidence that sparked the Zags as soon as they learned their opponent in this year's final.

"We were kind of rooting to meet them in the final again, and beat them," said Bekkering, who hit two key 3-pointers in the second half.

Gonzaga made a 9-2 run midway through the second half to pull away from the sixth-seeded Toreros (19-13), who came within a few minutes of completing a remarkable run. Kiva Herman concluded an outstanding tournament with 23 points and six rebounds for San Diego, which won three games in three days to reach the final against the top-seeded Zags.

"It wasn't necessarily that we lost to them," said Vandersloot, who added the tournament MVP award to her regular-season player of the year award. "It was just that we lost. We know how it feels to be on the other side of this. We felt like we came here with something to prove."

Herman got a huge postgame ovation from fans of both teams at the Orleans Arena. The senior forward scored 95 points in the Toreros' four games, breaking the tournament scoring record in their semifinal victory over second-seeded Portland.

The Zags earned their only previous NCAA appearance in 2007 by winning the WCC tournament. The double-bye format required Gonzaga to win only two games for this title, and the Zags did it with last season's failures on their minds.

"The game last year is what really drove us this season," Gonzaga coach Kelly Graves said. "We set a goal this year that it wasn't going to happen. We wanted to win the regular season championship, and we wanted to win the tournament championship. They kept their eyes on the prize all year, and it was ironic that it ended up being San Diego again."

After skidding into the WCC tournament with seven losses in their last 11 regular-season games, the Toreros became the lowest-seeded team to make the final since the conference expanded to eight teams in 1995.

"Both teams gave great fight," San Diego coach Cindy Fisher said. "My team had so much heart and so much desire, but fatigue set in in the second half. What an incredible run we had."

Dominique Conners had 13 points and six rebounds for San Diego, and Amber Sprague added 10 points and eight rebounds.

San Diego won its opening game over San Francisco on Friday before knocking off third-seeded Pepperdine on Saturday. The Toreros beat Portland with a second-half run, but the Zags made the only second-half move in the title game.

Gonzaga led 42-39 midway through the second half when Bekkering got rolling with two 3-pointers, including a basket with 9:38 left to put the Zags up 51-41. Bekkering also led the Zags with 10 rebounds.
